<i>Femme d’esprit</i></b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usyllestraefv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Syllestrae FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New Mod!</span><br>  Posts: 461<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/26/02 5:52:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=895.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Eh, an e-bay rant</span><hr size=1> Hmm,<br>
<br>
   I'll come out and speak from experience.<br>
<br>
   I never bought anything for EQ on E-bay, but I did buy a lightsabre (a unique crystal sword) for Diablo 2.  I had some money sitting in a paypal account and I was too lazy to go through the whole rigamarol to finish activating the account such that I could get the money mailed to me as a check (vs just spending the paypal money).<br>
<br>
   Why buy it?  It was rare enough in the game that I couldn't guarantee that if I stuck it out and just fought in the right areas I'd find it.  I might find it in one day, but it could be weeks and weeks, and I really wanted one.  The cost was roughly 3 hours of pay (after taxes), so I figured:<br>
Chance of finding sword after 2 hours Gameplay: 0.01%<br>
Chance of finding sword after working 2 RL hours overtime: 100%<br>
<br>
   It wasn't so much that I found the gameplay unpleasant (I quite enjoyed it actually), as much as I wanted that particular sword and there was no guarantee I could obtain one just by playing the game.  I had a lot more fun w/ the sword than I was having without it, so to me it was worth the price.<br>
<br>
   In a game like Diablo 2, where there's effectively 0 competition for spawns (because you can keep starting new games), the selling of items for RL money doesn't impact gameplay that much.  In EQ however, where there's a fixed pool of monsters to fight, if items are being sold on E-bay it can drive up the number of people hunting that item, which can cause crowding and other problems.  It's no fun if you're camping stormfeather to use the map yourself, and you're faced with twice as much player competition because half the people camping it want to sell it for RL cash.<br>
<br>
   Selling whole accounts (vs just items) is fairly related, but also fairly different, and I'll leave that for another reply so as to keep this one from gettin too wordy.<br>
<br>
- Syll <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usyllestraefv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Syllestrae FV</A> at: 6/26/02 5:53:42 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uburanmcmuffin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>BuranMcMuffin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/26/02 6:01:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=895.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Think before you sell.</span><hr size=1> ooc: This very problem had grown to be severe on The Nameless before I left. :P It was easily apparent in zones like OS, where even a moment of inattention can mean disaster for everyone, nevermind having a key member of the group be unfamiliar with cast times, aggro issues, etc. <br>
