<br>
   I think e-baying will always be a part of the MMOG scenario.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Always</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.  Not necessarily because there's people who want shortcuts, but because the game itself reacts impersonally to your character's wants and desires.  If I were playing a pen &amp; paper version of EQ, and I made it clear to my DM that I really wanted a Vorpal Doodad +3, he'd probably be willing to work out a quest of some kind somewhere along the line that would lead to the Vorpal Doodad +3 if it was within my range to obtain.<br>
<br>
   With MMOGs, you can tell the game as often or as much as you like that you want a Vorpal Doodad +3 and there's really no guarantee you're gonna even get the opportunity to obtain one.  If you're playing Ultima Online on one of the more populated servers, no amount of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> wanting</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> a house will get you one, because the land is all occupied.  I knew people with millions of gold who only had a straw shack because that's all they could find room to build.  The more demand exceeds supply, the more you'll see items sold for real world cash than in-game cash.<br>
<br>
   Some people make the argument that supplies need to be kept limited in order to keep the balance.  Items wouldn't be special if everyone had one.  But at the same time no one wants to be odd-man-out when it comes to items they want.  No one wants to come into Ultima Online and basically say &quot;Alright, every world needs homeless people, so I guess I'll take on that role.  Sure, my friend Joe Bob has his own castle with freaking dragons in the stables and a pool hall and a swimming pool, but I'll be damned if I haven't met some great folks in this dark alley I've staked out for myself&quot;.<br>
<br>
   Any time a game designer says &quot;We're going to add &quot;x&quot;, and to keep it special we're going to make it difficult and/or impossible to guarantee that one can obtain it&quot;, they're basically creating an E-bay market for that item.  If &quot;x&quot; is something that can't be traded (no-drop items, high levels, etc) then people will just sell the whole account.<br>
<br>
   Game companies can only go two routes really.  They can ban it all (ala EQ), or they can try to join in on the profit (ala UO, where you can pay a &quot;secure transfer fee&quot; to have ownership of an account permanently transferred to someone else).  Third route I guess would be creating some kind of system where through a reasonable amount of work, players could be guaranteed a reward equivalent to the effort they put into obtaining it.<br>
<br>
